  "prompt": "What is dyarchy and when was it introduced in India?",
  "response": "Dyarchy, also spelled dyarchi or diarchy, is a form of government in which two separate authorities govern the same area or territory. In the context of British India, dyarchy refers specifically to a system of governance introduced by the Government of India Act of 1919.\n\nThe Act introduced a dual system of governance for the provinces of British India, whereby certain subjects were to be administered by elected Indian ministers responsible to the legislative councils, while others remained under the control of the British government. Specifically, the governance was divided into \"transferred\" subjects, which were managed by Indian ministers, and \"reserved\" subjects, which were handled by the British-appointed Governor and his officials.\n\nDyarchy was implemented in the provinces of British India from 1920 and was aimed at improving Indian participation in governance, although it faced criticism and was seen as a limited measure that did not fully address the demands for self-governance. The system remained in place until it was replaced by further constitutional reforms in subsequent years.",
